Those who are part of the Pinya have to be strong - they can sometimes bear 770lbs on their shoulders. Castellers, as they are known, then form other levels and the top level is complete when the final climber, usually a small shild known as the enxaneta, reaches their position and puts one hand in the air.

Stages of assembly and disassembly should by completed without stopping.

Towers can reach up to 10 levels high.

The practice was declared an Intangible Cultural Heritage by Unesco in 2010 and teams compete at competitions between April and September each year.

